# new column with two values 'high' 'low' based on the income

def assing_income_range(x):
    if x == '$25,000-49,999':
        return 'Low'
    if x == '$100,000+':
        return 'High'

df['IncomeRange_HvsL'] = df['IncomeRange'].apply(assing_income_range)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This dataset originates from Prosper, the pioneering peer-to-peer lending platform in the United States, known for facilitating over $7 billion in funded loans. It comprises 113,937 individual loans, each associated with 81 distinct variables. These variables cover a wide range of loan characteristics, including loan amount, borrower interest rate, current loan status, borrower income, employment status, credit history, and the most recent payment details.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

We will examine the Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan, considering various factors like the borrower's rating, score, income, and other elements that might impact changes in the APR. Additionally, we'll investigate the factors contributing to fluctuations in the loan's interest rate.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Primarily, there are two key attributes that can assist in this inquiry:

Prosper Rating Prosper Score These factors may contribute to a lower Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) because a higher rating indicates a borrower's greater trustworthiness. Credit scores could have a similar impact on the Borrower's APR as Prosper Rating.

Loan interest rates are similarly influenced by these factors, as well as other characteristics such as Borrower Rate, among others.

# creating a fuction for ploting my histigram 
def hist_plot(df,x_value,bin):

    plt.figure(figsize = [15, 5])
    plt.hist(data = df, x = x_value, bins = bin);

    plt.title("BorrowerAPR Distribution")
    plt.ylabel('Count'.title(),fontsize=10,weight=("bold"))
    plt.xlabel(x_value.title(),fontsize=10,weight=("bold"));

  • Notably, there is a prominent peak in the distribution around the 31% mark.

Multivariate Exploration¶

In [28]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))

plt.ylabel('Borrowers APR (%)')
plt.legend(loc = 3, title='Terms (Months)');

Borrowers with a credit score of 6 or less tend to encounter lower borrowing rates when opting for a 36-month payment plan compared to both 12-month and 36-month plans. Conversely, borrowers with a credit score of 8 or higher tend to face higher borrowing rates when selecting a 36-month payment plan as opposed to either a 12-month or 36-month plan.

What is relationship of ProsperScore Rating and Loan Amount on BorrowerAPR¶

In [30]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))

Borrowers with higher score ratings tend to enjoy more favorable BorrowerAPRs, regardless of the loan amount they take. Conversely, borrowers with lower score ratings tend to face higher BorrowerAPRs, regardless of the loan amount they borrow.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expanded my analysis by conducting a multivariate investigation into Borrowers' APR, specifically examining how Prosper score ratings influence the relationship between Borrowers' APR and the loan amount. The multivariate exploration confirms the existence of a negative relationship between BorrowerAPR and the original loan amount. Generally, borrowers with lower score ratings typically have access to smaller loan amounts, while borrowers with higher ratings tend to access larger loan amounts.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

As indicated by the point plots, borrowers with lower scores tend to secure more favorable rates when seeking loans for 60 months compared to 12 and 36 months. Conversely, borrowers with higher scores often encounter higher rates when applying for loans with a 60-month term in contrast to 12 and 36 months.

Conclusions¶

  1. Higher BorrowerAPR rate is strongly related to higher BorrowerRate rate
  2. The most frequent loan amount collected by prosper borrowers is 4k followed by 15k and 10k
  3. Most of Prosper Borrowing rate fall around 36%
  4. Borrowers with lower scores tend to secure more favorable rates when seeking loans for 60 months compared to 12 and 36 months. Conversely, borrowers with higher scores often encounter higher rates when applying for loans with a 60-month term in contrast to 12 and 36 months.
